review_blob: Very good beer, with tropical fruit aromas. The 9% ABV isnt noticeable, at least not til later in the evening. Sadly, had a well-chilled, undisturbed 4-pack of 16 oz. cans, all of which were gushers. Ill have to change my jeans.

At the tap room. Nice, well balanced blend of toasty flavors and hippiness maybe a bit light on hops for style, but totally enjoyable and drinkable. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

From bottle. Almost no head, but good resins aroma, which carries over to flavor. Not excellent, but a solid IPA. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Roasty, with complex notes from chickory. Nice, full mouthfeel. Worth seeking out. 


---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

12 oz bottle - faint banana/clove aroma, golden, relatively clear appearance, off-white head that dissipates quickly, and a flavor that somehow seems to say "artificial flavors." It was $2.99 a sixer, once again proving you get what you pay for.
Poured from brown bottle. Light floral/grainy aroma, clear dark golden appearance with generous, lasting head. Sharp hops flavor, not as balanced by malt as Id like.

12 oz can into 16 oz. snifter (yeah, I know, a snifter is overkill for a lawnmower beer). Light, slight grain/corn aroma. Pours perfectly clear, golden, with reasonable head. Flavor of malt and corn; minimal hops. Not as thin as other lawnmower beers. Pretty good for a beer that comes in 30-pack cans.

Chewy describes this beer well. Theres no indication on the label whether its to be considered a stout or a porter, and knowing OSos reputation for "freestyle brewing," I dont think it should be pigeonholed into a particular style. Pours dark, with light tan head.  Roasty, nutty aroma, big mouthfeel, nice balance tends slightly toward malty sweet over hop bitterness. Great example of whatever style it is.

12 oz. bottle into 16 oz. snifter. Light tan head average at first, never completely dissipates. Roasty aroma, with hints of coffee and chocolate. Smooth, medium/full body, with flavors that progress toward slight bitterness as it stays on the palate. Very drinkable.

Bottle into a 16 oz. snifter. Pours copper/orange with frothy head that dissipates somewhat quickly. Earthy, saison-appropriate aroma with hints of citrus. Medium-full body with some bitterness lingering.

Sampled from bottle in 16 oz. snifter. Slight malty aroma; little hops. Appears amber/orange, slightly cloudy. A bit of sweetness upfront, with grainy overtones, yielding to a lasting, pleasant bitterness.
From the can. Pours hazy orange, lasting cream-colored head. Hop piney-ness a bit much for me, but balanced a bit by significant malt. A bit low on carbonation level.
